CENTRAL BANK DIGITAL CURRENCY (CBDC)
==================================

1. Definition
-------------
Central Bank Digital Currency (CBDC) is digital money issued by a
central bank, having the same value and legal status as physical cash.


2. Examples of CBDC
------------------
- India : Digital Rupee (e₹) issued by RBI
- China : Digital Yuan
- USA   : Digital Dollar (pilot)
- EU    : Digital Euro (proposed)


3. Key Features of CBDC
----------------------
- Issued by the Central Bank
- Legal tender (must be accepted)
- Backed by government
- Exists only in digital form
- Highly secure (DLT / blockchain-based)


4. Types of CBDC
---------------

4.1 Retail CBDC:
- Used by the general public
- Used for daily payments
- Similar to cash / UPI
- Example: India’s e₹-Retail (e₹-R)

4.2 Wholesale CBDC:
- Used by banks and financial institutions
- Used for inter-bank settlements
- Used in government securities
- Example: India’s e₹-Wholesale (e₹-W)


5. CBDC vs Cash vs Cryptocurrency
--------------------------------

Feature              CBDC            Cash            Cryptocurrency
Issuer               Central Bank    Central Bank    Private entities
Legal Tender         Yes             Yes             No
Physical Form        No              Yes             No
Value Stability      Stable           Stable          Volatile
Blockchain / DLT     Yes              No              Yes
Government Control   High             High            None


6. Why Countries Introduce CBDC
-------------------------------
- Reduce cash handling costs
- Prevent fake currency
- Faster digital payments
- Financial inclusion
- Better control over money supply
- Support digital economy


7. CBDC in India (Exam Important)
--------------------------------
- Introduced by : Reserve Bank of India (RBI)
- Name          : Digital Rupee (e₹)
- Technology    : DLT (Blockchain-based)
- Status        : Pilot phase
